{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491594"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"994"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/994"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.26,0.12,0.01,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30656"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/994"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-11-07T22:01:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T09:49:59+09:30","updatedAction":"updated","acceptedAt":null,"editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 21:17:32"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"994"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16599"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1368"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42192"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16599"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30656"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60 year old man presents with worsening shortness of breath, cough, and production of green sputum of 2-day length. He has no significant medical history, and is not on any medications. Chest x-ray shows consolidation in his right lower lobe. He is admitted to hospital overnight for treatment of community acquired pneumonia, commenced on IV fluids and benzylpenicillin and azirthromycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following morning during ward round he is reviewed and found to have an erythematous rash over his entire body, covering \u0026gt;95% of his body surface area (Image). He has no history of any allergies or skin conditions. He is haemodynamically stable with a blood pressure of 130/75, heart rate of 110, and is saturating at 98% on room air. His chest is clear with no wheezing or crackles, and his heart sounds are dual with no murmurs. The skin is very warm to touch, and it is slightly itchy, but there is no pain, scaling, or blisters. Nikolsky\u0027s sign is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the rash?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psoriasis","Toxic epidermal necrolysis","Atopic dermatitis","Tinea corporis","Erythroderma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely has \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythroderma \u003C/strong\u003Esecondary to commencing penicillin for his community acquired pneumonia. Erythroderma is an inflammatory skin disease with widespread erythema affecting \u0026gt;90% of the body surface area. The most common causes of this condition include: drug eruption, dermatitis, psoriasis, pityriasis rubra pilaris and haematological malignancies. Patients often present with a morbilliform (measles-like) eruption followed by exfoliation of the skin; however, this patient\u0027s erythroderma was noticed early prior to exfoliation. It is potentially life threatening, thus patients usually require admission for monitoring and haemodynamic stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EToxic epidermal necrolysis usually presents within a week of commencing antibiotic therapy, and is characterised by a prodromal illness, severe and rapid painful skin rash that is associated with a positive Nikolsky\u0027s sign, and often includes blistering or bulla of the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough psoriasis can cause erythroderma, it is not the likely cause in this patient as they have no history of psoriasis, and there are is no signs of scaling or exfoliation of the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETinea corpis is a superficial fungal infection that presents with itchy skin and characteristic ring-shaped lesions. This is unlikely in this patient due to the rapid onset of his rash and its widespread nature and diffuse redness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtopic dermatitis is not likely to present with an acute diffuse rash with no prior symptoms or rash. It most commonly occurs on the flexor surfaces of adults, and although acute flares are possible, they would not be this extensive.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Erythroderma is an intense and diffuse reddening of the skin followed by widespread exfoliation, and can be caused by drug eruption, dermatitis, psoriasis, pityriasis rubra pilaris and haematological malignancies."],"references":["Rothe MJ, Bernstein ML, Grant-Kels JM. Life-threatening erythroderma: diagnosing and treating the \u0022red man\u0022. Clin Dermatol. 2005 Mar-Apr;23(2):206-17. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2004.06.018. PMID: 15802214.","Mistry N, Gupta A, Alavi A, Sibbald RG. A review of the diagnosis and management of erythroderma (generalized red skin). Adv Skin Wound Care. 2015 May;28(5):228-36; quiz 237-8. doi: 10.1097/01.ASW.0000463573.40637.73. PMID: 25882661."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16599"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"994"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18480"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18480"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/39fdc453-fe33-4ca5-ab97-ccb4e6779cbf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/39fdc453-fe33-4ca5-ab97-ccb4e6779cbf.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":387}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16599"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-06T19:48:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-12-06T19:48:06+10:30","number":5,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"994"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30656"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"em